"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-womens-skateboarding-beauty-of-paris-sport-on-rise\", \"text\": \"PARIS \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 Inside the skateboard park at Place de la Concorde on Tuesday, fans braved blistering temperatures and no small amount of body odor poisoning the air around them. Why? Easy. They were watching the best women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s skateboarders in the world ply their trade in an Olympic final, inside a venue stuffed to the brim with people, colors, beats and food. Many could see the Luxor Obelisk\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094the gold-brimmed, ancient Egyptian centerpiece in the Place de la Concorde\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094from their seats, sometimes with skateboarders soaring into view in front of it. Others could spy the Eiffel Tower; still others, if they craned their necks, couldbehold the Arc de Triomphe, far off in the distance, or the Grand Palais.  Still, as the final unfolded round by round on Tuesday evening, fewer heads looked yonder and most every head looked down. Park skateboarding ranks among the most visceral of Olympic sports. There are 540-degree spins\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 think: one full spin and another half, while flying through the air and, ideally, landing on a skateboard. There are body varials that incorporate those spins, boards rotating along with bodies. There are, in the sport\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s parlance, shreds and hips, along with flips, handplants, spins and grinds. It\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s part art; it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s all athleticism.  The discipline doesn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t need a setting that drops jaws. But it has one, anyway.  The park itself resembled a moon crater, dropped into the middle of Paris proper. And, as these Paris Games unfolded and concerns over everything from security to its city-centered nature faded far from view, skateboarding became something of a centerpiece. This place exuded joy. So did the competitions.  Andy Macdonald, the veteran British competitor\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094and by veteran, we mean, he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s51\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094described the difference, for skateboarding specifically, from Tokyo to Paris. Beyond the obvious (no fans, now fans), he said that, in Tokyo, when skateboarding made its Olympic debut, most athletes were \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009ca little gun-shy\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d about how officials and television networks would present their sport\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094and how that presentation would be perceived. But on the day ofthe men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s street finalslast week, Macdonald saw what everyone here saw: \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cOne of the best finals ever.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  He also gave one anecdote that highlighted the sport\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s popularity in Paris. Tony Hawk, the most iconic figure in skateboarding\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s not-so-short history, couldn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t get enough tickets to bring his entire family to an event he was attending.  On Tuesday, that combination of venue, elite athletes and the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s park final followed the same formula, enhancing skateboarding\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s place in the Olympics. Specifically,theseOlympics.  Consider Sky Brown, for example: Born in Japan to a Japanese mother and British father, she began skateboardingandsurfing at age 3. She went viral for the first time a year later, after her father posted a video of her shredding\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094concrete, not waves\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094on social media. She was the youngest-ever Vans U.S. Open of Surfing participant, in 2016 at age 8. She was the only girl on her school\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s soccer team at 10. She turned pro in skateboarding one year after that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094and soon became the first female competitor, ever, at any age, to land a frontside 540. She was 11.  Soon, she wonDancing with the Stars: Juniorsand landed a Nike sponsorship in 2018. She survived a 15-foot fall, soaring up a halfpipe only to plummet back toward concrete. That landing, still brutal to even watch, fractured her skull and left arm, while lacerating her heart and lungs. A helicopter flew Brown to the hospital, as she went in and out of consciousness, then straight into the ICU. The Tokyo Games were only a few months away. She recovered enough to compete in them, gifted additional time from the delay caused by the global pandemic, and won a bronze medal in park skateboarding to boot. This made her both Great Britain\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s youngest-ever summer Olympian and youngest medal winner. She was 13.  Brown is 16 now. She doesn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t have a coach. She doesn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t need one. She became the first female skateboarder to complete a 540 and then a 720 at the X Games. She currently splits the year in half, living in her hometown and in the U.S. She trains with Shaun White, teaches English pop stars to skateboard, and yet, ranksMean Girlsamong her favorite movies. She arrived in Paris after another round of injuries to recover from (MCL tear, dislocated shoulder). She packed an Olympic backstory into her luggage, and she arrived here among the favorites.  That\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s just one story, of one competitor, nine lives lived in 16 short years. Brown wanted to compete in Paris, because she saw her sport evolving\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094each routine more technical and advanced, the competition stiffer than the boards underneath the athletes\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 feet\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094and she wanted to be a part of that push. After one practice early into the Games, she was struck by how loud the crowd screamed. Brown went opposite Allen Iverson in her description. She was talking aboutpractice; here, as a spectacular spectacle that gifted competitors energy and drive. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s going to be sick,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she said.  Just as Australia\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Arisa Trew described the venue heading into the competition. Only 14 herself, and, like Brown, a surf-skate dual-sport athlete, Trew almost qualified to Tokyo but didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t quite make the Aussie team. She came to Paris determined to make up for not being an Olympian \\u00e2\\u0080\\u00a6then age 11. She described the vibe the same as Brown had.Sick. She also revealed that she loved glancing at the Eiffel Tower while mid-air in practice runs. Also sick.  And, yes, they were right. Sick, it was.  The preliminary round Tuesday whittled the field from 22 competitors to eight. Judges considered the difficulty in the competitors' chosen tricks, along with their style, their flow and their use of available terrain. Each run lasts for 45 seconds. Most presented the sport\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s duality\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094pure, remarkable athleticism balanced by the poetry of choice. What Brown later called \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cthe beautifulness of skateboarding,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d more or less.  The final featured two medalists from Tokyo\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094Brown and Cocona Hiraki, the silver medalist in the discipline\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s debut. All faced stiffer competition than three years ago with Trew, Naia Laso (Spain), Dora Varella (Brazil), Bryce Wettstein (U.S.) and a deep field.  When the final kicked off in the early evening, general consensus had already formed. Scores around 90 or above were likely necessary to approach medaling. Anyone who wanted to medal probably had to break that mark.  There were miscues early, perhaps owing to the stage and its inherent stakes. Laso lost control of the board underfoot toward the end of her first run. Trew started hers to oohs and aahs, but \\u00e2\\u0080\\u00a6 same. Hinano Kusaki (Japan) false-started. All the mistakes, when combined, allowed room for other competitors to surge up the leaderboard. Wettstein, the American, went first; her run was captivating, good for an 88.12. She held the lead then\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094but not for long. Hiraki took it back, scoring 91.98, as the first round of runs concluded.  Up, up, up the scores inched as skateboarders soared skyward\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094one toward five colorful rings (on the near horizon) and the obelisk (on a more distant one). One did a backward flip afterward, using her board as a launch point, then launching with both hands.  Hiraki still led after the second round of final runs. Laso, one of the favorites before a back injury, continued to compete valiantly despite the injury. She hadn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t broken 60 after two attempts cruising through the park.  Trew, though, began to stand apart. She broke 90 in her second time down, then upped that in her third run. She sort of resembled a ballet dancer, on a skateboard, by her favorite landmark, the Eiffel. What a sentence. She smiled a lot. She dazzled even more. Brown would later admit that her injured shoulder hurt throughout the competition, and it hurt worse after she crash-landed on it.  She gutted out a 92.31 score in her third run, which was good enough for bronze. In that same final round, Hiraki matched her Tokyo performance, upping her score (92.63) and sliding into second for the silver.  Which left Trew, the 14-year-old Aussie, all smiles and soars, equal parts adorable and fierce. Make no mistake, she\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s an athlete, a competitor and a force. She\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s also a teenager, and that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s meant with zero disrespect. In fact, it was refreshing to watch her afterward, gold medal secured but face absent either pressure or relief. Those who want to wring their hands about the age of skateboarders should also view this most healthy of approaches. Olympic final.Sickcourse. Killer run. Gold medal.  And then: \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m just going to keep skating and pushing myself and having fun with my friends,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Trew said.  She sounded sincere, and that, right there, was the wild part. Because Trew and the women sitting next to her or skateboarding here in Paris are changing not just how Parisians view this X Games event-turned-Olympic sport. They\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099re changing how it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s competed, which will change how the whole world looks at them\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094and soon.  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Greg Bishop is a senior writer for Sports Illustrated who has covered every kind of sport and every major event across six continents for more than two decades. He previously worked for The Seattle Times and The New York Times. He is the co-author of two books: Jim Gray\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s memoir, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cTalking to GOATs\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d; and Laurent Duvernay Tardif\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cRed Zone\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d. Bishop has written for Showtime Sports, Prime Video and DAZN, and has been nominated for eight sports Emmys, winning two, both for production. He has completed more than a dozen documentary film projects, with a wide range of duties. Bishop, who graduated from the Newhouse School at Syracuse University, is based in Seattle.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"